<br>
He seemed to float towards the darkened barn, carried by the night’s unwholesome thickness. Soundlessly he scaled the barn-side like a fly on a glass. The old thatched roof of the building was worn through in several places and the dark figure attached a rope to the frame. He began to climb slowly and deliberately down into the barn.        <br>
<br>
On the floor the assassin could make out the vague shape of a sleeping human. A sly smile crossed the rogue’s face and in a flash of pale sickening green light he began to change. His skin darkened to ebon his eyes burned red and he nearly doubled in height. <br>
<br>
The transformation awoke the sleeping human. He was no older than twenty and had a full head of yellow hair that shimmered strangely in the green light. In his eyes was the wild look of a hunted animal. “Draehith! but no you cant be your...” the human trailed off his mind now in the full paralysis of fear.<br>
<br>
The assassin’s smile broadened and from his cloak he pulled a thin long bladed dirk. The sight of the blade caused the man to react and he searched for his own weapon.  His hand grasped a long sword but by the time he looked up his attacker was gone blending seamlessly into the night. His breath quickened and he turned quickly around vainly trying to pierce the darkness with feeble eyes. At that moment the clouds parted and a single ray of silvery light lit the barn. The assassin dark and tall was illuminated clearly but it was too late. His blade was already swooping downward, preparing to give the human a mortal blow. The man slumped forward the blade buried in his back. As swiftly as he came the rogue was gone. Once again carried in the bosom of the night.<br>
