<br>
“Click buzz whirr you are to report to master Lobal Postluger immediately click,” the infernal machine said in a hollow voice.<br>
<br>
Menbik eyed the courier angrily debating whether to turn it into scrap metal. He let the idea slide and climbed back into bed. About an hour later he arose again and dressed himself in a simple work vest and woven pants. In his boot he stuck a long simple dirk on his belt he sheathed his rapier.<br>
<br>
Menbik was young for a gnome, barely out of adolescence. He was only beginning to bald and faint streaks of brown could still be seen in his pearly white hair.  He donned his watcher badge and stepped outside his door into the cavernous city of Ackanonn. He paused for a moment and gazed idly in the river at his green tinted reflection.<br>
<br>
 It was comforting to be home he thought.  Since he had enlisted it seemed that he was rarely there. He had wanted to be a soldier originally, like his brother. A gate guard perhaps or possibly stationed somewhere in the steam front mountains close to home. The watchers had other plans however.<br>
<br>
Menbik awoke from his daydream and continued onward down the lit path leading towords the temple of Bristlebrane. He paid his respects to his deity and walked into a shady unlit corner of the temple. He turned quickly to see if anyone was watching and slipped through the illusionary wall. Behind the wall was an unlit narrow corridor sloping downward. Menbik’s keen eyes pierced the veil of darkness and he made his way carefully through the jagged passageway.<br>
<br>
He came at last to a large dimly lit hall. He nodded greetings to familiar faces half hidden in shadows. At the end of the hall sat an ancient figure. His face was creased deeply from laughter and his eyes were kind and gentle. Menbik was not fooled by the spymaster’s appearance. The jolly old gnome was as likely to stab you in the back as to shake your hand if he thought it would benefit the throne.<br>
        <br>
“It does me well to see you my boy,” said the aged spymaster<br>
        <br>
“ You sent for me?” Menbik replied angrily<br>
        <br>
“I see your manner has not changed though I suppose there is no time for pleasantries. I’ve an assignment for you, it would seem that Draehith lives.”<br>
